{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480606"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"83"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"83","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/83"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.02,0.03,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"83"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"83","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/83"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"83"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44952"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4459"},{"type":"tags","id":"4460"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42963"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA MET call is made for a  33-year-old woman in the delivery suite with acute blood loss following vaginal delivery 40 minutes ago. She has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her pregnancy was uncomplicated and she delivered a 4.1 kg baby. The placenta was delivered with active management and was reported as complete with intact membranes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has lost 1400 mL of blood in the last 10 minutes. Her uterus is palpated above the umbilicus and deviated to the right. She takes no regular medications. On examination, her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. The midwife has established intravenous access and commenced crystalloid fluids.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bimanual uterine massage and intravenous oxytocin","Manual removal of placenta","B-Lynch suture","Genital tract examination","Emergency hysterectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with primary postpartum haemorrhage (PPH) due to uterine atony, evidenced by the boggy uterus palpable above the umbilicus. The blood loss is significant at 1400 mL in 10 minutes, requiring immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBimanual uterine massage and intravenous oxytocin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step. This helps contract the uterus, compress blood vessels, and expel blood clots. Oxytocin (10 units intravenously) should be given simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManual removal of placenta\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the placenta has already been delivered and was documented as complete with intact membranes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB-Lynch suture\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical technique used when medical management fails to control PPH. It requires laparotomy and is not an appropriate first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenital tract examination\u003C/strong\u003E is important but should be performed after initial measures to control bleeding have commenced, typically in theatre where adequate exposure and analgesia can be provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency hysterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a last resort when all other measures have failed to control life-threatening haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for PPH in this case included diabetes mellitus and fetal macrosomia (4.1 kg). The management of PPH requires a systematic approach following the four T\u0027s: Tone (most common), Tissue, Trauma, and Thrombin. Additional management should include ongoing fluid resuscitation, blood product replacement if needed, and consideration of additional uterotonics such as ergometrine or misoprostol.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bimanual uterine massage and oxytocin are first-line treatments for postpartum haemorrhage due to uterine atony.","Primary postpartum haemorrhage is defined as blood loss \u003E500mL within 24 hours of delivery.","Risk factors for postpartum haemorrhage include macrosomia, diabetes, and high parity."],"references":["Bienstock JL, Ahizechukwu CE, Hueppchen NA. Postpartum haemorrhage. N Engl J Med 2021;384:1635-45. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33913640/","WOMAN Trial Collaborators. Effect of early tranexamic acid administration on mortality, hysterectomy, and other morbidities in women with post-partum haemorrhage (WOMAN): an international, randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial. Lancet. 2017 May 27;389(10084):2105-2116. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28456509/","Mavrides E, Allard S, Chandraharan E, Collins P, Green L, Hunt BJ, et al. Prevention and management of postpartum haemorrhage. BJOG 2016;124:e106\u2013e149. Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Prevention-and-Management-of-Postpartum-Haemorrhage.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44952"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"83"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44952"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T12:48:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-08T12:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"83"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59543"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"t